{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499483"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:00:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:00:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1515"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1515"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.73,0.03,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49200"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1515"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34318"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"451"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42333"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49200"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents with a painless lesion on his lip that has been increasing in size for the last 2 months (image). He has a 20 pack year smoking history. He is otherwise well with no significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Syphilis","Aphthous stomatitis","Herpes simplex"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis painless lesion on the lower lip of the middle aged man had been present for several months. It has the raised, rolled edges suggestive of malignancy and the site - the vermillion - is a common site for\u003Cstrong\u003E squamous cell cancers\u003C/strong\u003E. Squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) is often described as firm, raised nodule/plaques with a crusted or scaly surface that can present as a chronic non healing ulcer. Some of the risk factors for SCC are tobacco, chewing of betel nuts , fair skin , older age and sun exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESCC\u003C/strong\u003E of the lip comprises 25-30% of oral cancer and usually begins as a premalignant lesion. Incidence of SCC of the lip is declining globally possibly due to the increased use of sun protectants like lip balms. Some 400 new cases occur every year in Australia. Prognosis however is excellent with a 5-year survival rate of 90% due to how it often presents early, being in a visible location and having a slow growth pattern. However, once it does spread regionally to lymph nodes, survivability drops to 50% Management requires surgical excision or topical creams like fluorouracil or cryotherapy if surgical removal is unsuitable,\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma \u003C/strong\u003Eusually appears on the upper lip with similar risk factors of fair skin and sun damage. Nodular BCC is the most common type, is also slow growing and rarely a threat to life. Differentiating it from SCC can be noticed with the characteristic shiny/pearly nodule with a smooth surface and central ulceration, resulting in rolled edges.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAphthous stomatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is extremely common and provides a painful punched out sore on the oral membranes. The cause of it is not clearly defined yet but is suspected to be attributed to a reaction to the protein of the mucosal tissue. Recurrent ones even tend to begin as a round yellow spot with a red halo that breaks down to a punched-out ulcer with a white/grey/yellow membrane. Investigations are rarely required unless there are several, severe or recurrent. Treatment is symptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lesions of \u003Cstrong\u003Esyphilis\u003C/strong\u003E, chancre, tend to be short-lived and aphthous, described as solitary, small firm with a well-defined margin and indurated base. The ulcer also will heal without treatment within weeks before progressing to secondary syphilis.\u00a0\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex ulcer \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be mild or subclinical but is usually extremely painful and tender. The patients often have a foul breath, swollen easily bleeding gums along with fever, restlessness and excessive drooling. The vesicles often evolve to ulcers and the lymph nodes will be enlarged and tender. Recovery is brief and usually is done in 2 weeks.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A classical feature of squamous cell carcinomas are raised rolled edges."],"references":["Han AY, Kuan EC, Mallen-St Clair J, Alonso JE, Arshi A, St John MA. Epidemiology of Squamous Cell Carcinoma of the Lip in the United States: A Population-Based Cohort Analysis. JAMA Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2016;142(12):1216\u20131223. doi:10.1001/jamaoto.2016.3455","Ramji R. Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma in skin of colour [Internet]. Oakley A, McGivern M, editors. DermNet. 2017 [cited 2022Nov15]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/cutaneous-squamous-cell-carcinoma-in-skin-of-colour","Ngan V, Oakley A. Syphilis [Internet]. Vanousova D, Bray S, editors. DermNet. 2020 [cited 2022Nov15]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/syphilis","Oakley A. Herpes simplex [Internet]. DermNet. 2015 [cited 2022Nov15]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/herpes-simplex"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34318"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1515"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18271"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18271"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4a131ee6-4b07-4452-bf92-d6e23c6f9211.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4a131ee6-4b07-4452-bf92-d6e23c6f9211.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":396}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34318"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-25T09:27:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-25T09:27:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1515"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49200"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nul